 tract"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral corticospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for voluntary control of fine, precise movements, particularly of the distal limbs. It carries approximately 90% of all descending motor fibres from the primary motor cortex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other tracts have different functions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReticulospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E controls posture, balance and automatic movements\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVestibulospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E maintains balance and posture in response to head position changes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior corticospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E primarily controls axial and proximal limb muscles\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERubrospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E facilitates flexor muscle tone and is less prominent in humans compared to other mammals\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lateral corticospinal tract decussates in the medulla, which explains why motor deficits appear on the contralateral side of the body following a unilateral upper motor neuron lesion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The lateral corticospinal tract carries approximately 90% of descending motor fibres and is crucial for fine, precise movements of the distal limbs.","The lateral corticospinal tract decussates at the level of the medulla oblongata.","Damage to the lateral corticospinal tract results in impaired voluntary movement, particularly affecting fine motor control of the hands and fingers."],"references":["Javed K, Reddy V, Lui F. Neuroanatomy, Lateral Corticospinal Tract. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534818/","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). 